The website of the PAX Protection of Civilians program contains general information about the program and its projects, our latest publications and blog posts, partners, and more.

The PAX PoC Annual Report 2019 reflects upon the first reporting period for the Protection of Civilians (PoC) program, initiated in September 2019. This document provides detailed project-level reports for all 4 core initiatives under the program: Engaging International Actors (EIA), Human Security Survey - Iraq (HSS-IQ), Human Security Survey - South Sudan (HSS-SS), and Protection in Practice (PiP). These provide additional analysis as to the key results achieved during the reporting period, complemented by featured stories and further reflections from our partners.

The PAX PoC Annual Report 2019 reflects upon the first reporting period for the Protection of Civilians program, “initiated in September 2019. This document contains a high-level summary providing insights into the program’s overall progress during the initial inception phase; as well as relevant context analysis, updates regarding program management, lessons learned, and a financial overview.

The PAX PoC Annual Report 2019 reflects upon the first reporting period for the Protection of Civilians (PoC) program, initiated in September 2019. This document contains key annexes, including: a list of acronyms; an overview summary of the program’s results areas and corresponding performance indicators; and an organogram highlighting all relevant staff, partners, and key counterparts at the Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Ministry of Defense.

This interactive dashboard shows the results of the Human Security Survey (HSS) in Iraq. Results are presented per survey round and governorate, and can furthermore be disaggregated by gender. The dashboard consists of five thematic pages, namely demographics, security context & threats, vulnerability, security actors, and future expectations, and a sixth page on methodology.

This interactive dashboard shows the results of the Human Security Survey (HSS) in South Sudan. Results are presented per survey round and state, and can furthermore be disaggregated by gender. The dashboard consists of five thematic pages, namely demographics, security context & threats, vulnerability, security actors, and future expectations, and a sixth page on methodology.

Results of the Freedom from Fear Alliance consist of the number of observed positive changes that in a plausible way can be related to stated objectives and the efforts of the alliance and its local partners. Obviously, the number of observed changes by 1/1/2016, is 0.
# of community members reached with the IEC materials, campaign, events, radio messages

Community dialogues: 3-day meetings facilitated by PAX and partners, organized to inform and consult various groups of local communities, such as local government officials, local security providers and local civil society representatives. The meetings have two main purposes: present the HSS survey data (and receive their feedback), and to discuss among community groups what should be done and prioritized concerning the local security situation. Relevant authorities: Both formal authorities (government officials from state, county or payam level, formal police or army leadership) and informal authorities like (paramount) chiefs and armed youth leaders, etc.

DD3: # times L&A targets include CSOs in the decision making process + number of times L&A targets react upon the positions of the CSOs by adopting their argumentation and terminology + number of times L&A targets react upon the positions of CSOs by putting their issues on the agenda

Community engagement activities: Follow-up activities that address the action plan discussed and agreed at the community dialogue (e.g. focus group discussions, workshops, public campaigns, radio talk shows, awareness raising events, sports or other cultural activities as part of peacebuilding messages). This does not include the community dialogues themselves or advocacy meetings organized by PAX or partners. Community committees: Groups of volunteers formed by participants from the community dialogues representing various groups and institutions within society, mandated by the community dialogue to address the main community security priorities discussed and agreed in the action plan. These follow-up activities are also known as community engagement activities.
DD1: # concrete changes in practices of targeted governments, private sector and societal actors.
DD2: # concrete or significant changes in laws, policies and/or norms/attitudes

Community dialogues: Short and targeted meetings, facilitated by PAX and partners, with community members/local civilians, local authorities (elected and appointed officials) and local security providers in attendance. At times, sessions are held separately with each group initially to address all concerns, and then a joint session is held with all parties in attendance, depending upon political and security conditions at the local level.
DD5: # first and second tier partners with increased L&A capacities.
Attendees: Registered participants who take part in at least one in-person or virtual conference session. Attendees are unique and counted once even if they participate in a multi-day event.
